text: A nod to 1950s Notting Hill and the first West-Indian migrants with a version of Lord Kitchener's splendid calypso 'London is the Place for Me.' Hugh Boneville's comic timing is as good as ever,Sally Hawkins ridiculously cute, Nicole Kidman deliciously malevolent,Peter Capaldi does a rousing turn as the nosy neighbour. Thank goodness it was a VERY British film about a very British hero. I read these stories to my son as a child and we watched this film as he was a few years older. No sex or violence, no moronic obvious slapstick (apart from the ear wax and the drinking water from the toilet). It left me with the kind of warm glow I would leave the cinema with as a child. Truth is,if you have kids yourself and haven't become an embittered old drunk or a teenager aged between 9 and 95, you might like this too. I could go on but I'm not a film reviewer. There's some seriously bitter people on this page, as there are all over the net I'm afraid. Okay, bearing in mind that I worked in the Natural History Museum and seeing as a lot of it is filmed in there I MIGHT be biased....

text: While this movie wasn't that good, it was certainly nowhere near as bad as Chipmunks or Smurfs. It had charm and had some very funny writing and gags in some parts.   Sure, it wasn't very Paddington-ish, but it could have been a million times worse than what we got.   Live action movies based on children's characters do have potential to be decent. They're just ruined with unecesarry pop culture references, topped off with immature writing that dumb them down for brain dead adults to laugh at with their clueless 4 year olds.   They don't challenge people or give them any valuable thoughts to think about in the future. They just pander to modern trends. They're pretty much just junk food for your mind.
